1
00:00:05,975 --> 00:00:13,997
Hello everyone, my name is Michał Drozdowski and I'm a creative director at Elevenbit Studios.

2
00:00:15,677 --> 00:00:18,118
And I'm Przemek Marszał, an art director at Elevenbit.

3
00:00:19,758 --> 00:00:25,460
Yes, and we are together kind of responsible for the game development at Elevenbit Studios.

4
00:00:26,463 --> 00:00:34,489
So we want to talk today about the lesson from Frostpunk and This War of Mine and ask ourselves a general question of why to make games.

5
00:00:35,650 --> 00:00:37,831
And who is 11bit Studios?

6
00:00:39,132 --> 00:00:43,796
We are a company from Poland that started about 10 years ago.

7
00:00:44,636 --> 00:00:51,061
We started four person with Grzegorz Michalski, Bartek Brzostek, Przemek and me as partners.

8
00:00:51,801 --> 00:00:53,623
Currently we are about 100 people.

9
00:00:56,168 --> 00:01:02,064
Our two recent projects are Frostpunk and This War of Mine, and those are the games

10
00:01:02,084 --> 00:01:02,927
that we will talk about.

11
00:01:05,303 --> 00:01:10,486
So, we like to think that what we are doing is called meaningful games.

12
00:01:11,447 --> 00:01:16,230
And with such a word, it's always a question, what do we mean by that?

13
00:01:16,551 --> 00:01:17,691
What are meaningful games?

14
00:01:18,312 --> 00:01:24,696
And I think there are a lot of ways to see what can be meaningful from different approach.

15
00:01:24,896 --> 00:01:30,480
And we also in the studio have some different ideas about what we call meaningful games.

16
00:01:30,561 --> 00:01:32,222
But let us first sum up.

17
00:01:33,602 --> 00:01:37,003
And one thing that is important for us

18
00:01:38,163 --> 00:01:42,404
is that we all are very emotional about games and about playing games.

19
00:01:43,064 --> 00:01:47,405
And those emotions, especially those emotions that breed thoughts

20
00:01:48,145 --> 00:01:50,046
is something that we want to have in our game,

21
00:01:50,566 --> 00:01:54,486
which means that we would like to have emotions that are not shallow,

22
00:01:55,127 --> 00:01:59,347
but that came up from mostly decisions and subjects that we touch.

23
00:02:00,228 --> 00:02:01,068
And we also think that...

24
00:02:02,030 --> 00:02:13,686
It would be great if games could communicate some values, some greater values, in the process of making them and through the message they send to the community.

25
00:02:14,467 --> 00:02:24,119
We really look for fresh experiences and not only fresh ideas, but also things that could probably

26
00:02:24,980 --> 00:02:30,866
expand the game language about, like for example making empathy games like this one of mine,

27
00:02:30,946 --> 00:02:32,128
which is kind of...

28
00:02:33,671 --> 00:02:36,352
not a mechanic, but something that is really important in the game.

29
00:02:36,892 --> 00:02:41,194
And we tried to make those games with a kind of close-to-life message,

30
00:02:41,775 --> 00:02:45,917
something which is insightful and something which is well-precised.

31
00:02:46,457 --> 00:02:49,138
We could kind of put it in one sentence.

32
00:02:49,718 --> 00:02:52,399
And if we look at the games that we made,

33
00:02:53,060 --> 00:02:55,221
for this War of Mine we had like two messages.

34
00:02:55,341 --> 00:02:57,802
It was at war, not everyone is a soldier,

35
00:02:58,642 --> 00:03:01,684
and that war always happens at somebody's doorstep.

36
00:03:02,584 --> 00:03:06,530
which actually means that we want to make a game about civilians.

37
00:03:07,912 --> 00:03:13,340
With Frostpunk, that was society survival and the last city must survive, which also

38
00:03:13,500 --> 00:03:18,768
kind of was meaning that we will make a game about society and the cost it pays for survival.

39
00:03:23,078 --> 00:03:24,638
Okay, we will switch now for a few minutes.

40
00:03:25,378 --> 00:03:32,160
So, why we made those games that Michal told you about?

41
00:03:32,960 --> 00:03:34,280
We will start with This War of Mine.

42
00:03:34,901 --> 00:03:39,222
Because, to be honest, this presentation forced on us

43
00:03:40,182 --> 00:03:42,802
to question ourselves why we made these games.

44
00:03:44,343 --> 00:03:45,243
So, why This War of Mine?

45
00:03:48,863 --> 00:03:54,488
You know, when I recall from the beginning of my early career,

46
00:03:54,508 --> 00:03:58,551
let's say it's career, or early days in game development,

47
00:03:59,712 --> 00:04:02,895
it's probably for you the same. I just love to make games,

48
00:04:03,195 --> 00:04:08,519
and we all love totally to make games, and we love it for the creativity,

49
00:04:09,420 --> 00:04:12,403
and also to express ourselves, and to stand out.

50
00:04:14,401 --> 00:04:20,566
But, and this love for games and also the innovation behind the games was behind,

51
00:04:21,447 --> 00:04:27,152
also behind the vision why we created 11-bit studios. Because we wanted to express and we

52
00:04:27,172 --> 00:04:31,956
wanted to innovate. At the time that we started working on this World of Mine,

53
00:04:33,312 --> 00:04:40,578
We are after few games, we already finished I think Anomaly 2 or some other mobile games

54
00:04:41,339 --> 00:04:47,364
and we, after Anomaly and Anomaly 2, we understood that we could deliver

55
00:04:49,045 --> 00:04:55,469
something that is well packed, well thought out innovation.

56
00:04:55,529 --> 00:04:57,090
It could do an innovative game.

57
00:04:58,831 --> 00:05:00,772
And we started working on some other project.

58
00:05:00,832 --> 00:05:01,713
It was called Shelter.

59
00:05:02,333 --> 00:05:06,116
And after I think eight months of the development,

60
00:05:06,176 --> 00:05:08,397
we are at the stage that.

61
00:05:08,888 --> 00:05:11,569
okay, this is good gameplay, this is a good game,

62
00:05:11,609 --> 00:05:14,030
but there is something lacking, you know?

63
00:05:14,530 --> 00:05:18,591
And we just couldn't agree to this approach

64
00:05:18,631 --> 00:05:24,072
that we will create mechanic gameplay-based game only.

65
00:05:24,612 --> 00:05:30,954
And I think unconsciously set the bar higher for us

66
00:05:31,114 --> 00:05:35,475
because we were looking for some other height for us.

67
00:05:37,995 --> 00:05:40,417
And we just scrapped the project.

68
00:05:41,738 --> 00:05:45,601
And we understood that we need emotions in our games.

69
00:05:45,721 --> 00:05:47,723
We need to define an emotion in our games,

70
00:05:47,763 --> 00:05:48,823
we find an emotions,

71
00:05:49,344 --> 00:05:51,906
and find something that we would like to

72
00:05:52,026 --> 00:05:54,768
and would love to talk about in those games.

73
00:05:56,656 --> 00:06:06,983
And we scrapped the shelter and to be honest it was visually, it had almost the same camera,

74
00:06:07,023 --> 00:06:11,286
it was also very cross-section, but it was a completely different game.

75
00:06:12,467 --> 00:06:17,491
And we went back to the drawing boards and we asked all people in the team,

76
00:06:17,611 --> 00:06:21,814
hey guys, let's think of this game, what we'd like to talk about.

77
00:06:23,015 --> 00:06:32,825
And I think this is one of the moments in our development that we had luck, to be honest.

78
00:06:33,125 --> 00:06:37,930
We had luck that we had such a wonderful team and that we are open-minded.

79
00:06:39,471 --> 00:06:44,893
At this time, Greg, our CEO, once came to the company and he said,

80
00:06:44,953 --> 00:06:53,595
guys, you know, I was reading this article about civilians in Sarajevo, in Bosnia and Herzegovina,

81
00:06:54,656 --> 00:07:03,298
and it was a really strong emotional piece. And he told us about it and he said, hey,

82
00:07:04,499 --> 00:07:07,260
what do you think about it? And when he told it,

83
00:07:08,562 --> 00:07:16,926
we immediately understood the huge importance of what we could do and what we could achieve

84
00:07:18,006 --> 00:07:25,110
with this game. We understood that wow, before us there was a project that could change our lives

85
00:07:25,290 --> 00:07:28,852
and it was, you know, instant revelation.

86
00:07:30,400 --> 00:07:33,262
So we thought, okay, let's do this.

87
00:07:33,582 --> 00:07:35,403
It's a huge and risky project.

88
00:07:35,843 --> 00:07:37,664
To be honest, until the end of production,

89
00:07:37,764 --> 00:07:39,685
until the day of the launch,

90
00:07:40,166 --> 00:07:42,907
we didn't know how the people will react to this game.

91
00:07:43,308 --> 00:07:46,269
It could be just, you know, cool, artistical piece,

92
00:07:46,750 --> 00:07:49,211
and without any significance

93
00:07:49,331 --> 00:07:51,793
to the game development as a whole.

94
00:07:53,454 --> 00:07:54,254
But we went for it.

95
00:07:54,654 --> 00:07:58,156
We knew the risk, but also we knew this importance.

96
00:07:59,716 --> 00:08:03,078
And we had this message that Michał already told you,

97
00:08:04,478 --> 00:08:05,819
that was easy to understand.

98
00:08:06,839 --> 00:08:09,340
And overall, I think it had value.

99
00:08:09,861 --> 00:08:11,801
It was huge value for us.

100
00:08:11,862 --> 00:08:15,123
It was personal value, artistical value,

101
00:08:15,483 --> 00:08:16,604
and emotional value.

102
00:08:17,164 --> 00:08:20,225
And we saw this value for our next project.

103
00:08:21,446 --> 00:08:25,148
So I think that was why we started working on this work of mine.

104
00:08:26,652 --> 00:08:28,073
So, how we made it?

105
00:08:28,873 --> 00:08:31,075
We'll just present you some ideas how we made it.

106
00:08:32,075 --> 00:08:36,678
But I will start with some two basic concept that we follow

107
00:08:37,699 --> 00:08:40,461
and the concept that we agree while we are doing games.

108
00:08:40,561 --> 00:08:42,682
First of all, when you are doing something innovative,

109
00:08:42,782 --> 00:08:44,563
when you are doing some new game,

110
00:08:44,583 --> 00:08:47,005
in our case, meaningful game,

111
00:08:50,107 --> 00:08:54,629
For us, it always touches completely new areas of game development.

112
00:08:54,669 --> 00:08:59,772
So if you follow innovation, you must agree that it will be a constant R&D process.

113
00:09:00,993 --> 00:09:10,338
From the start till the end, you will constantly, as I love to say, sail in unexplored oceans.

114
00:09:10,778 --> 00:09:11,699
And you must agree to this.

115
00:09:13,048 --> 00:09:17,871
And second concept that we also follow is,

116
00:09:19,652 --> 00:09:23,133
we, you know, there are studios that make games,

117
00:09:23,534 --> 00:09:27,496
okay, let's make the most beautiful game that we have,

118
00:09:27,816 --> 00:09:32,438
or let's decide that gameplay is the most important part

119
00:09:32,498 --> 00:09:35,319
of our game, or the art, or something different,

120
00:09:35,380 --> 00:09:35,880
or the music.

121
00:09:36,340 --> 00:09:38,001
For our studio, it's different.

122
00:09:38,999 --> 00:09:44,746
Because we think for us, the mood, the experience is the key.

123
00:09:45,567 --> 00:09:51,193
Mood as this bond between gameplay and art, and also music.

124
00:09:51,274 --> 00:09:53,216
I haven't written it down here, but...

125
00:09:54,117 --> 00:09:56,959
Everything must create a mood and experience.

126
00:09:57,479 --> 00:10:01,262
And this is what we pursue when we create our first prototype.

127
00:10:01,742 --> 00:10:04,985
We pursue from the early days of the development,

128
00:10:05,225 --> 00:10:09,168
we pursue to find the mood in our games.

129
00:10:10,912 --> 00:10:17,975
And what's funny is that when we have, let's say we are in the middle of the production,

130
00:10:18,395 --> 00:10:26,879
we start to do our focus tests on the players, so our QA is inviting people to the studio

131
00:10:27,799 --> 00:10:30,340
and we have those questions after the tests.

132
00:10:33,322 --> 00:10:37,105
some, let's say, how would you like to value the graphics?

133
00:10:37,185 --> 00:10:38,906
How would you like to value the mechanics?

134
00:10:39,287 --> 00:10:41,369
And how would you like to value mood?

135
00:10:41,809 --> 00:10:43,931
And tons of different questions.

136
00:10:44,631 --> 00:10:46,433
For our games, when I recall,

137
00:10:46,573 --> 00:10:48,254
it was for this, for mine and Frostpunk,

138
00:10:48,855 --> 00:10:53,479
always the highest ranked question was the mood.

139
00:10:54,179 --> 00:10:58,883
So I think we do it in the right direction.

140
00:11:04,460 --> 00:11:11,624
Okay, so let's go and see a few things about the design that we did in this War of Mine.

141
00:11:12,084 --> 00:11:19,547
And it's like Przemek said, when you start up on a subject like the war, you usually have some kind

142
00:11:19,587 --> 00:11:25,670
of concept in your mind. You've seen some movie, you read some book, and it's good to kind of empty

143
00:11:25,710 --> 00:11:32,373
your head and to make, you know, like the saying that you cannot fill a glass that is not empty,

144
00:11:32,393 --> 00:11:33,553
you have to first empty the glass.

145
00:11:34,154 --> 00:11:37,955
And we did research, and I think this is a very important part of the project.

146
00:11:38,375 --> 00:11:43,518
The other thing that we'll talk about later will be the core kind of system of players' part and decision,

147
00:11:43,998 --> 00:11:49,500
and I will show you also some kind of design consequences of some design choices that we made.

148
00:11:50,508 --> 00:11:57,531
So it's pretty much obvious that you will better understand the reality of the game if you do some research.

149
00:11:58,011 --> 00:12:04,253
But you will actually grab this mood that Przemek is talking about

150
00:12:05,014 --> 00:12:11,636
and you will grab a lot of, really a lot of detail and nuances that you haven't been aware of before.

151
00:12:12,637 --> 00:12:17,679
And I think that's very important, especially when I have new people coming to the project.

152
00:12:18,499 --> 00:12:29,347
Usually they have some different approach to the game and they first have to kind of redo the research that we did, read some book, view some movie, to kind of get better understand what was the reality at this time.

153
00:12:30,488 --> 00:12:33,491
And the other thing that you get...

154
00:12:34,505 --> 00:12:35,886
is you get facts about the world.

155
00:12:36,546 --> 00:12:38,567
And what's interesting is this,

156
00:12:38,608 --> 00:12:42,930
that these facts actually define a lot of situation

157
00:12:42,970 --> 00:12:44,190
that you will have in the game.

158
00:12:44,711 --> 00:12:46,672
So if, for example, we have snipers

159
00:12:46,732 --> 00:12:48,313
that operate during the daytime

160
00:12:48,693 --> 00:12:51,054
and constant shelling that is also operating

161
00:12:51,074 --> 00:12:51,915
during the daytime,

162
00:12:52,475 --> 00:12:54,816
we know that civilians will be active at night

163
00:12:54,876 --> 00:12:55,656
and during the night,

164
00:12:56,057 --> 00:12:57,798
and it actually goes to the design

165
00:12:57,858 --> 00:13:00,559
of having people staying during the day at home.

166
00:13:01,900 --> 00:13:08,141
getting active at night out of their home. And another, if you have no tap water, you have no

167
00:13:08,201 --> 00:13:14,382
electricity, then you have to get water and kind of, I don't know, create some, I mean, cook some

168
00:13:14,442 --> 00:13:19,503
food without electricity. So it goes immediately to some kind of, okay, so I need some parts to

169
00:13:19,523 --> 00:13:28,425
scavenge to kind of get like a water collector or maybe create a stove for burning wood and

170
00:13:28,465 --> 00:13:30,706
burning books. So these facts...

171
00:13:31,643 --> 00:13:37,767
are not only facts that kind of go into narrative, but they go pretty much into the design.

172
00:13:38,767 --> 00:13:45,352
And another thing that we kind of observed when we were doing research is that basically this war

173
00:13:45,452 --> 00:13:52,956
is not one constant narrative event that has a beginning and an end, but it's a situation that is

174
00:13:53,617 --> 00:13:55,438
made up of stories.

175
00:13:56,318 --> 00:14:02,980
who affect certain people, like a story of a mother who lost a child, or a story of two

176
00:14:03,300 --> 00:14:09,222
grandparents that they don't know what to do during the war time. So the research kind

177
00:14:09,282 --> 00:14:15,684
of had impact on how we have structured the narrative in the game, so making it like a

178
00:14:15,824 --> 00:14:21,685
puzzle built up, many, many, many stories put together in one picture of the war.

179
00:14:23,744 --> 00:14:30,913
And if we go down and if we look at the core of the gameplay, we get to a situation where

180
00:14:30,973 --> 00:14:34,657
we're talking about the player path and the decision that it's making.

181
00:14:35,218 --> 00:14:40,945
And one thing we learned about the war is that it kind of affects very much

182
00:14:42,070 --> 00:14:44,251
ourselves and change us and

183
00:14:45,311 --> 00:14:50,934
the question is really how much of what we believe we are. Are we going to keep and

184
00:14:51,354 --> 00:14:53,675
protect during this hard time?

185
00:14:54,236 --> 00:15:00,839
So for us it was really important that the player is free to choose his own path and that this path will kind of lead him

186
00:15:01,259 --> 00:15:04,580
from kind of being a villain or being a hero,

187
00:15:05,341 --> 00:15:07,662
doing something great or maybe something very bad.

188
00:15:08,522 --> 00:15:15,084
So this was achieved of course through decision-making, but another important thing in this decision-making,

189
00:15:15,164 --> 00:15:18,686
in this world of mine, was that he must face the consequences.

190
00:15:18,846 --> 00:15:26,408
So he's able to do whatever he wants, but he must know what was the consequences of his act.

191
00:15:26,848 --> 00:15:35,771
And either he can see it, or he can be informed, or he can be kind of informed by the people from the shelter.

192
00:15:37,138 --> 00:15:40,740
Because we wanted not to judge the player by the decision,

193
00:15:40,820 --> 00:15:42,601
but we wanted to create a moral world

194
00:15:43,161 --> 00:15:47,104
that will kind of feedback him about what he's thinking

195
00:15:47,304 --> 00:15:48,645
about his decision making.

196
00:15:49,225 --> 00:15:50,926
And this was very important to get this look,

197
00:15:50,986 --> 00:15:53,908
okay, choose your own path, make your own decision,

198
00:15:53,988 --> 00:15:56,309
but kind of face the consequences

199
00:15:57,030 --> 00:16:00,312
and see how the world react to your actions.

200
00:16:02,533 --> 00:16:03,614
And most of these.

201
00:16:04,599 --> 00:16:09,021
feedback was actually made through kind of questions like

202
00:16:10,062 --> 00:16:11,462
Should we have been doing this?

203
00:16:12,863 --> 00:16:16,845
or grandpa, why do other people why do people kill each other and

204
00:16:17,705 --> 00:16:19,226
What we wanted to achieve we wanted

205
00:16:19,866 --> 00:16:26,570
To achieve some kind of interaction with the player when we will ask him questions that he will have to answer himself

206
00:16:27,010 --> 00:16:33,073
In his head and kind of think of what he's doing kind of think of where does those action leads him?

207
00:16:35,507 --> 00:16:41,368
And for the last, I would like to show you how some initial guidelines affected some

208
00:16:41,408 --> 00:16:46,210
design rules, because I think it's also interesting that usually when we try to define a subject,

209
00:16:46,250 --> 00:16:51,372
we are writing a sequence of words or short sentences, and then those things translate

210
00:16:51,432 --> 00:16:52,332
into game design.

211
00:16:52,852 --> 00:16:57,754
And for example, when we defined that this will be a game about civilians, we were thinking,

212
00:16:57,854 --> 00:17:00,654
OK, it will be a game about people like us, normal people.

213
00:17:01,075 --> 00:17:03,075
And what does that mean in terms of game design?

214
00:17:03,959 --> 00:17:05,339
We actually had no level ups.

215
00:17:06,940 --> 00:17:11,781
We played the game and it was really luring to kind of, you know, improve your skill in

216
00:17:11,841 --> 00:17:16,202
some place, but we throw it away because this is not what's happening in real life.

217
00:17:16,903 --> 00:17:23,824
And we also were very lured by having some kind of RPG-like inventory, so we had like

218
00:17:24,325 --> 00:17:29,146
initially a few slots for the item that you can take from the Savage to your shelter.

219
00:17:29,866 --> 00:17:34,850
and then you could have a helmet or you could have a kevlar vest or you could have some picklocks

220
00:17:35,571 --> 00:17:39,634
and it was very tempting to make separate slots for these items

221
00:17:40,274 --> 00:17:43,337
but we said no, we don't have separate slots like that

222
00:17:43,777 --> 00:17:47,020
and if you're wearing a kevlar vest it's probably heavy enough

223
00:17:47,300 --> 00:17:49,922
and you can't bring that much stuff from the scavenge.

224
00:17:51,030 --> 00:17:52,811
Also the personality of the people.

225
00:17:52,851 --> 00:17:53,751
They have skills.

226
00:17:53,991 --> 00:17:56,652
Some skills are very useful, like someone is quick

227
00:17:56,732 --> 00:17:58,593
or someone is quite strong,

228
00:17:58,653 --> 00:18:01,534
but there are also useless skills, like I'm good at maths.

229
00:18:02,355 --> 00:18:04,536
I mean, what does it give me if I'm good at design

230
00:18:04,576 --> 00:18:05,316
and more happens?

231
00:18:06,036 --> 00:18:06,317
Nothing.

232
00:18:08,917 --> 00:18:15,163
We have of course personal belief and psychological traits of the character, so not everybody

233
00:18:15,183 --> 00:18:15,844
is an angel.

234
00:18:15,884 --> 00:18:21,169
There are people who are egoistic, there are people who are altruistic, and they all kind

235
00:18:21,209 --> 00:18:24,652
of give you feedback depending on the individual nature.

236
00:18:25,433 --> 00:18:30,137
We have people able to suffer trauma like the post-traumatic war syndrome.

237
00:18:31,097 --> 00:18:36,298
in the game and for example another kind of design decision that was to be made

238
00:18:36,459 --> 00:18:40,539
based on the fact that there are people like us is that it's very easy to be

239
00:18:40,579 --> 00:18:44,800
killed in the game and it's very easy to kill and the combat is rather kind of

240
00:18:44,900 --> 00:18:50,602
chaotic. Sometimes you don't know when the bullet hits you and this is also kind of

