00:35:18,470 --> 00:35:24,273
The decision is not yet very bad in terms of influencing the society,

465
00:35:24,973 --> 00:35:29,115
but it's kind of up to you how you will use it later in the game.

466
00:35:29,615 --> 00:35:35,698
And when we go even further, we start getting things like propaganda certain,

467
00:35:36,318 --> 00:35:41,000
like a pledge of loyalty or a forceful persuasion.

468
00:35:41,460 --> 00:35:44,481
So this tree is kind of going the dark side.

469
00:35:45,390 --> 00:35:47,892
from the light part to the dark part.

470
00:35:48,713 --> 00:35:52,175
And it's up to you.

471
00:35:52,396 --> 00:35:54,277
I mean, this is a bit counterintuitive

472
00:35:54,337 --> 00:35:56,619
because in games usually when you have a skill tree,

473
00:35:57,079 --> 00:35:59,521
at the very end, you receive a big prize.

474
00:36:00,081 --> 00:36:01,723
It's not like that in Frostpunk.

475
00:36:01,863 --> 00:36:06,266
At the end of the tree, you receive a very strong tool

476
00:36:06,586 --> 00:36:07,907
to influence the society,

477
00:36:08,568 --> 00:36:12,171
but it's actually something really, really nasty.

478
00:36:12,771 --> 00:36:12,871
And...

479
00:36:13,612 --> 00:36:20,957
We're coming to a statement that actually in Frostpunk, not signing a law that pushes the system further

480
00:36:21,558 --> 00:36:30,064
is quite a valid decision to be made. It's quite valid to stop at the level that you feel comfortable with and try not to go further.

481
00:36:32,292 --> 00:36:38,916
So it's not matters only what law you sign, but it also matters whether how you use them,

482
00:36:39,236 --> 00:36:41,057
if you use them or if you abuse them.

483
00:36:41,437 --> 00:36:46,880
And this is kind of a mechanic that we introduced that, for example, if you have guards, you

484
00:36:46,920 --> 00:36:51,103
can start dispersing the crow each time the people protest.

485
00:36:52,183 --> 00:36:55,405
But doing that means that your guards will feel kind of...

486
00:36:56,869 --> 00:37:03,437
allowed to perform the peaceful operation on their own behalf.

487
00:37:05,179 --> 00:37:09,724
So we kind of during the game measure how you are using the abilities.

488
00:37:14,311 --> 00:37:17,534
the shaping of the society actually happened at the moment when

489
00:37:18,055 --> 00:37:22,118
the law you have introduced, the concept that you have introduced in your society

490
00:37:22,919 --> 00:37:25,061
starts to kind of live their own life

491
00:37:25,582 --> 00:37:27,163
and it all begins by kind of

492
00:37:27,884 --> 00:37:31,487
creating some kind of split in the society

493
00:37:31,928 --> 00:37:34,630
so for example on the screen you have a woman who was assaulted

494
00:37:35,671 --> 00:37:40,494
It's after the signing of a law, the Pledge of Loyalty, and it's a woman that has been

495
00:37:40,554 --> 00:37:44,476
assaulted by her neighbor who accused her of informing on him.

496
00:37:44,996 --> 00:37:48,418
But she hasn't signed the Pledge of Loyalty, so she is not guilty.

497
00:37:48,939 --> 00:37:53,881
But the trick is that the society is already split into two different sides.

498
00:37:54,522 --> 00:37:58,244
Those who like the kind of law and those who don't like.

499
00:37:58,904 --> 00:38:01,186
And this goes further and further until...

500
00:38:01,966 --> 00:38:10,249
people's, the society start to shape, to get a shape that you kind of might not accept or not be comfortable with.

501
00:38:12,110 --> 00:38:22,614
And what I wanted to talk more also is that we try to, by addressing all this hard subject, we try to be conscious about the message and we try to kind of

502
00:38:24,129 --> 00:38:28,692
being very careful about how we're shaping the communication, what we are saying.

503
00:38:29,473 --> 00:38:33,856
And there were months of polishing the message during the company. But there were also these

504
00:38:33,936 --> 00:38:40,501
questions of hard subjects like, should we talk about cannibalism? This is something very nasty.

505
00:38:41,757 --> 00:38:43,078
But on the other hand, it happens.

506
00:38:43,318 --> 00:38:45,179
It happens, for example, during wartime,

507
00:38:45,619 --> 00:38:47,840
during long siege of the city in winter

508
00:38:47,901 --> 00:38:49,942
when soldiers start eating horses,

509
00:38:50,002 --> 00:38:51,302
then they start eating rats.

510
00:38:51,382 --> 00:38:52,643
And then maybe at some times,

511
00:38:53,123 --> 00:38:54,884
somebody eats some other people.

512
00:38:56,972 --> 00:39:06,980
The question was not how not to talk, if not to talk, or sweep it under the carpet, but how to talk about them, how to make this similar to real life.

513
00:39:07,320 --> 00:39:10,843
And for example, as it goes for cannibalism, it kind of made it...

514
00:39:12,044 --> 00:39:17,250
a kind of event that happened in a situation where the people are really starving for a long time

515
00:39:17,810 --> 00:39:23,076
and they really kind of forced to do so and this is a small event that you can actually close your

516
00:39:23,176 --> 00:39:27,922
eyes and say okay I didn't see that or you can protest and say no that won't happen in my city.

517
00:39:28,722 --> 00:39:32,884
And because Frostpunk is also a game that kind of touched all those subjects,

518
00:39:32,984 --> 00:39:38,647
it's still a dystopian game of kind of a fictional reality,

519
00:39:39,087 --> 00:39:43,450
but we felt compelled to kind of make an end quote and kind of sum it up.

520
00:39:44,050 --> 00:39:47,072
And if the player kind of crossed the line, Kavdor,

521
00:39:47,873 --> 00:39:53,417
gone too far with shaping the society

522
00:39:53,877 --> 00:39:56,979
and paid a too high price for the survival,

523
00:39:57,319 --> 00:39:58,620
we wanted to stress that out.

524
00:39:58,740 --> 00:40:00,922
We wanted to say, hey guy, you crossed the line.

525
00:40:01,542 --> 00:40:02,363
That's a bit too far.

526
00:40:02,863 --> 00:40:05,945
But this is also a moment when we think that many people

527
00:40:06,005 --> 00:40:07,967
may kind of ask themselves a question,

528
00:40:08,007 --> 00:40:09,908
why, why do you say that?

529
00:40:09,948 --> 00:40:11,709
Why, did I really?

530
00:40:11,770 --> 00:40:14,511
And they start to kind of remember and find out

531
00:40:14,592 --> 00:40:15,912
if they did or they did not.

532
00:40:24,078 --> 00:40:24,198
So.

533
00:40:26,112 --> 00:40:34,414
Again, we have this, the art, the art, art section in a game as it is so important here for us.

534
00:40:36,075 --> 00:40:38,015
So, how we approach it?

535
00:40:40,936 --> 00:40:50,538
We, first of all, we looked at our game, we thought about our game and we created a list of adjectives.

536
00:40:52,854 --> 00:40:53,635
What is it for?

537
00:40:54,636 --> 00:40:55,436
This is our...

538
00:40:56,297 --> 00:40:59,138
This was the situation we were thinking about this way.

539
00:40:59,218 --> 00:41:04,422
Okay, so let's say this hypothetical situation.

540
00:41:05,637 --> 00:41:09,800
what we would like our gamer to say

541
00:41:10,300 --> 00:41:13,782
when he sees our screen of our game.

542
00:41:14,563 --> 00:41:17,525
And we wanted to imagine, okay,

543
00:41:17,885 --> 00:41:20,767
what we want him to see in our game

544
00:41:20,867 --> 00:41:26,431
and then what we wanted for this player

545
00:41:26,451 --> 00:41:27,772
to tell us about this game.

546
00:41:28,072 --> 00:41:29,293
And those were the adjectives.

547
00:41:29,333 --> 00:41:31,215
So what I'm seeing, I'm seeing cold.

548
00:41:32,155 --> 00:41:33,096
I'm seeing city.

549
00:41:34,348 --> 00:41:37,930
I'm seeing serious game and so on and so on.

550
00:41:38,350 --> 00:41:42,752
So we've listed the things that we wanted at the end

551
00:41:42,832 --> 00:41:45,314
to have on the screen, on each screen of our game,

552
00:41:45,334 --> 00:41:46,834
we wanted to see this.

553
00:41:47,114 --> 00:41:48,875
Maybe not on each, but as a whole,

554
00:41:48,915 --> 00:41:53,377
we wanted this player to see those keywords.

555
00:41:53,758 --> 00:41:54,918
We call them adjectives.

556
00:41:55,921 --> 00:41:59,805
We also had some kind of product guidelines and stuff like this.

557
00:41:59,845 --> 00:42:07,953
So we had this bible of how we would like the player to receive the visuals of the game.

558
00:42:08,934 --> 00:42:13,318
So the second thing is, OK, we wanted to understand what does the code mean.

559
00:42:13,338 --> 00:42:18,663
For the whole time we were researching it and stuff like this.

560
00:42:20,545 --> 00:42:27,431
During the production it wasn't made on purpose, but it just told us a lot about the situation.

561
00:42:27,831 --> 00:42:30,794
So we understood what cold is about.

562
00:42:31,715 --> 00:42:35,478
I personally like hiking, I like hiking in winter,

563
00:42:36,019 --> 00:42:42,545
and during the production we've also been to the rather high mountain in Poland.

564
00:42:46,068 --> 00:42:50,450
And there were really, really nasty temperatures then.

565
00:42:50,470 --> 00:42:52,931
And the cold was so terrifying.

566
00:42:53,111 --> 00:42:56,052
And it was such... it was the situation you...

567
00:42:56,952 --> 00:42:58,713
You couldn't do much with it.

568
00:42:59,153 --> 00:43:01,654
And it was so overwhelming around you.

569
00:43:01,674 --> 00:43:03,635
We had frostbites and stuff like this.

570
00:43:03,795 --> 00:43:05,956
And when we then came to the studio, we said...

571
00:43:06,836 --> 00:43:12,919
oh wow, we really again are doing a really serious game.

572
00:43:13,679 --> 00:43:18,101
And this cold, you know, you can imagine what cold is.

573
00:43:18,601 --> 00:43:21,983
So it's also a plus for a game to be easily imaginable.

574
00:43:23,924 --> 00:43:25,365
So then we thought.

575
00:43:26,402 --> 00:43:31,326
Okay, from the visual standpoint, how we would like this game to be, what is also important

576
00:43:31,366 --> 00:43:37,251
for us, we wanted to have this distinctive look for our game, and wanted to have this

577
00:43:37,831 --> 00:43:43,636
look for the whole time, and wanted this player to remember Frostpunk is this game, and wanted

578
00:43:44,497 --> 00:43:50,162
to have the situation when he sees the screen, this player says, wow, this is Frostpunk.

579
00:43:51,162 --> 00:43:57,503
So, as you saw, Michael already showed you the paper prototype.

580
00:43:58,444 --> 00:43:59,584
Then we've made concepts.

581
00:44:00,824 --> 00:44:03,705
Then it was our first playable prototype.

582
00:44:04,025 --> 00:44:06,985
As you can see, it's very different from where the game ended.

583
00:44:07,325 --> 00:44:12,566
But still, the whole as a key art element was there.

584
00:44:12,906 --> 00:44:16,307
And in the center we had this generator.

585
00:44:18,468 --> 00:44:19,448
That's how it finished.

586
00:44:19,688 --> 00:44:21,248
We have again, we have the hole,

587
00:44:21,288 --> 00:44:22,849
we have the center of the generator,

588
00:44:22,869 --> 00:44:25,810
we have this radial system and stuff like this.

589
00:44:26,850 --> 00:44:30,011
So we have this key art and key look for the game.

590
00:44:30,871 --> 00:44:31,972
We have this objectives.

591
00:44:33,152 --> 00:44:35,733
We knew what we would like to feel at the end,

592
00:44:35,833 --> 00:44:37,873
how what we'd like, what the player would like to feel

593
00:44:37,913 --> 00:44:39,374
at the end when he sees the game.

594
00:44:41,074 --> 00:44:43,875
And then we have this problem.

595
00:44:44,989 --> 00:44:49,274
Okay, we aren't that huge and we won't be able to do everything with this game.

596
00:44:49,314 --> 00:44:58,126
We won't be able to have this option to, for example, zoom the camera totally close and

597
00:44:58,226 --> 00:45:00,489
see all the people walking around in Frostpunk.

598
00:45:01,050 --> 00:45:02,051
So we had to decide.

599
00:45:02,071 --> 00:45:02,612
We had to have...

600
00:45:03,473 --> 00:45:06,715
create conscious decisions of how we'd like to split the game

601
00:45:07,075 --> 00:45:08,756
and how we'd like to approach the game.

602
00:45:09,757 --> 00:45:13,319
And on each of these approaches, on these three layers,

603
00:45:13,799 --> 00:45:15,060
we wanted to have the purpose.

604
00:45:15,700 --> 00:45:19,202
So first view was the city view of the game.

605
00:45:19,762 --> 00:45:21,523
And as you can see, it was for the building,

606
00:45:21,743 --> 00:45:23,624
management, and world changes.

607
00:45:24,850 --> 00:45:26,372
And how we realize it?

608
00:45:26,953 --> 00:45:29,015
We wanted the player to see cold,

609
00:45:29,395 --> 00:45:31,798
steampunk wanted to see city,

610
00:45:32,278 --> 00:45:35,622
and wanted to have this, see our unique art system.

611
00:45:36,083 --> 00:45:40,828
So as you can see, the camera is set in the certain point,

612
00:45:41,108 --> 00:45:44,111
we never go back to, come too close

613
00:45:44,151 --> 00:45:46,374
to the characters in the game.

614
00:45:46,995 --> 00:45:49,398
We have the city, it's a city builder game.

615
00:45:49,799 --> 00:45:53,084
You can manage this, you can operate on this.

616
00:45:53,484 --> 00:45:54,906
You can see the city changing.

617
00:45:55,808 --> 00:45:57,190
You can see the architecture.

618
00:45:57,651 --> 00:46:02,778
So this layer of the art was for the city.

619
00:46:04,048 --> 00:46:08,370
The second layer was for talking about the society and its problems.

620
00:46:08,930 --> 00:46:14,853
And this is the layer that we decide, okay, this is the layer where we will show people, the real people,

621
00:46:15,413 --> 00:46:16,834
but we will approach it...

622
00:46:19,515 --> 00:46:22,976
this way so it won't be so heavy in production.

623
00:46:23,977 --> 00:46:26,297
So we find out the style for it,

624
00:46:26,818 --> 00:46:29,299
we realize we won't be able to do it in real time

625
00:46:29,839 --> 00:46:34,441
and we focus on showing the emotions of the people,

626
00:46:34,581 --> 00:46:41,003
on showing the situations the game has for you, ready for you.

627
00:46:42,859 --> 00:46:46,681
And the third layer was a map layer.

628
00:46:47,082 --> 00:46:49,903
And it was, we want to have this feeling

629
00:46:49,943 --> 00:46:52,905
that this game is not just this small hole,

630
00:46:53,486 --> 00:46:55,447
but there is a whole world around it.

631
00:46:56,148 --> 00:46:59,610
And there is this epic world you can also explore.

632
00:47:00,110 --> 00:47:03,592
And it was for this, and this world was for you

633
00:47:03,672 --> 00:47:07,335
to have a bigger breath and to rest a bit,

634
00:47:07,375 --> 00:47:08,756
go out and rest a bit.

635
00:47:11,117 --> 00:47:18,642
And we found the look for it, the way we could emphasize the cold and also the scale.

636
00:47:20,003 --> 00:47:23,786
So, I think we also delivered the message.

637
00:47:23,926 --> 00:47:28,989
And I think this game, of course you can tell if we did it well,

638
00:47:29,029 --> 00:47:37,315
but I think at the end we have the society survival game from the design and the gameplay standpoint,

639
00:47:37,475 --> 00:47:39,216
and also from the art standpoint.

640
00:47:40,343 --> 00:47:47,144
So, you already know why we made those games and how we made those games, but I would like

641
00:47:47,164 --> 00:47:55,106
to tell you a bit more and just to give you some, let's say maybe influence on you and

642
00:47:55,246 --> 00:48:04,588
tell you some another idea behind my personal idea on how can you approach your own whys

643
00:48:04,788 --> 00:48:05,828
and why to make games.

644
00:48:06,648 --> 00:48:08,508
So, there are many whys.

645
00:48:09,249 --> 00:48:12,169
You can approach the games from totally different perspectives.

646
00:48:13,130 --> 00:48:15,690
You can make the games for your own joy.

647
00:48:16,010 --> 00:48:20,532
You can make games to talk about real life, for fresh experiences.

648
00:48:20,572 --> 00:48:21,952
They're all whys.

649
00:48:23,052 --> 00:48:30,415
But I would like to only tell you about one why that I'm finding very, very close to me

650
00:48:30,475 --> 00:48:30,935
right now.

651
00:48:31,435 --> 00:48:34,996
And it's an idea of responsible development.

652
00:48:35,727 --> 00:48:37,468
So, where do I start?

653
00:48:38,328 --> 00:48:43,432
We, you all know that we are, we aren't IT, we are an entertainment.

654
00:48:44,272 --> 00:48:49,776
So, if you are an entertainment, we have movies, we have books and we have games.

655
00:48:51,417 --> 00:48:52,417
And all of this...

656
00:48:53,388 --> 00:48:54,429
fight for one time.

657
00:48:55,329 --> 00:48:59,511
Because this user won't be able to stretch the time.

658
00:48:59,551 --> 00:49:02,912
So when he decides that he wants to have a love story,

659
00:49:03,632 --> 00:49:06,453
this player will decide if he will pick the book

660
00:49:06,513 --> 00:49:09,595
or if he will pick the video or movie

661
00:49:09,695 --> 00:49:12,676
or he will ultimately pick the game.

662
00:49:14,722 --> 00:49:22,045
And it's not only my observation, because you may have seen it, but like Nintendo of America said recently,

663
00:49:22,525 --> 00:49:27,347
I compete for time, not against Xbox or PlayStation.

664
00:49:27,887 --> 00:49:34,430
So, you know, the huge players understand, we aren't competing for something,

665
00:49:34,870 --> 00:49:39,452
we are just competing for this time, and we need to have the value in what we give.

666
00:49:40,673 --> 00:49:42,594
So, if you look at this this way...

667
00:49:44,124 --> 00:49:52,853
Games, I think, would explore at the end all genres, all values, all experiences to feel

668
00:49:53,134 --> 00:49:54,395
different users' times.

669
00:49:55,997 --> 00:49:59,841
And if we look at these games, movies, and books...

670
00:50:01,028 --> 00:50:03,609
you know, look at, okay, let's deliver our genres,

671
00:50:03,649 --> 00:50:06,091
values, and experiences, we can go further.

672
00:50:06,571 --> 00:50:09,032
And okay, so say, maybe in the future,

673
00:50:09,092 --> 00:50:10,273
games might be new books.

674
00:50:10,793 --> 00:50:14,335
So you could pick the genre, pick a love story,

675
00:50:15,296 --> 00:50:20,078
pick a drama, pick a strategy, and read it, so play it.

676
00:50:20,859 --> 00:50:26,102
And if we emphasize the value in this statement,

677
00:50:26,722 --> 00:50:27,883
we can go even further.

678
00:50:29,097 --> 00:50:31,638
we can say that games might be new school readings.

679
00:50:32,699 --> 00:50:35,179
And not only school readings for the students,

680
00:50:36,580 --> 00:50:38,441
that's what's already happening,

681
00:50:39,021 --> 00:50:42,282
but it could also be in elementary schools.

